giraffe.library/G_Arc

    NAME
	G_Arc -- draws an elliptical arc.

    SYNOPSIS
	void G_Arc( a0:drawable, struct GC *a1:gc, LONG d0:x, LONG d1:y, ULONG d2:width, ULONG d3:height, LONG d4:ang1, LONG d5:ang2 );

    FUNCTION
	Draws an arc defined by an ellipse [(x/a)^2+(y/b)^2=1].  The
	size of the ellipse (a,b) is given by width and height.  And the
	origin is given by (x,y).  An incomplete arc can be produced
	by giving the two angles.  The value of 360 degrees is 
	given in the header file giraffe.h as G_2pi.  The
	thickness of the arc can be controled using gc.LineWidth.

    INPUTS
	drawable     -- either a bitmap or a layer.
	gc           -- user initialized graphics context.
	x,y          -- center of the ellipse.
	width,height -- size of the ellipse.
	ang1,ang2    -- angle swept by arc.

    RESULT

    BUGS

    SEE ALSO
	G_Wedge()

giraffe.library/G_BeginUpdate

    NAME
	G_BeginUpdate -- limits clipping to the damagelist.

    SYNOPSIS
	BOOL G_BeginUpdate( G_Layer a0:layer );

    FUNCTION
	Sets the layer visibility only to the internal damagelist
	for more efficient refreshing of a layer.  The damagelist
	is automatically cleared assuming that the layer is to
	be properly refreshed.
	  During this time, the layer is locked so that no other
	processes may interfere with the refresh.  When done call
	G_EndUpdate().
	  Because the layers without full clipping do not have 
	their own cliplist or damagelist for that matter, all 
	refreshes should begin with a full layer and then nest
	into their children.  If you begin refreshing just a 
	non-clipped layer, G_BeginUpdate() will return false 
	indicating that the cliplist has not been changed.

    INPUTS
	layer -- a valid layer pointer.

    RESULT
	result -- returns TRUE if damagelist was not empty.  NULL
	          means that the layer needs no refreshing.

    SEE ALSO
	G_EndUpdate()

