giraffe.library/G_UseFont

    NAME
	G_UseFont -- increments the font usecount.

    SYNOPSIS
	G_Font G_UseFont( Font a0:font );

    FUNCTION
	When a font is shared by many different owners the internal
	usecount can be incremented so that each has it's own
	hook into the font.  Then each may call closelayer() independently
	when they are done.

    INPUTS
	G_Font -- font to be shared.

    SEE ALSO
	G_OpenFont(), G_CloseFont()

giraffe.library/G_UseLayer

    NAME
	G_UseLayer -- increments the internal usecount value.

    SYNOPSIS
	G_Layer G_UseLayer( G_Layer a0:layer );

    FUNCTION
	Used in conjunction with G_DropLayer() this allows a task to
	keep the layer pointer valid even if the layer has been
	passed to G_CloseLayer() by some other task.  The layer is
	not actually removed from the tree until the internal usecount
	reaches zero.

    INPUTS
	layer -- a valid layer pointer.

    RESULT
	G_Layer -- the same pointer.

    SEE ALSO
	G_DropLayer()

giraffe.library/G_Wedge

    NAME
	G_Wedge -- draws a pie wedge.

    SYNOPSIS
	void G_Wedge( a0:drawable, struct GC *a1:gc, SHORT d0:x, SHORT d1:y, USHORT d2:width, USHORT d3:height, SHORT d4:ang1, SHORT d5:ang2 );

    FUNCTION
	Draws a wedge from an area filled ellipse.  The ellipse is 
	defined the same as in the arc() function.  The angles range
   	from 0 to 255 for a complete arc.  So 64 = 90 degrees.

    INPUTS
	drawable     -- either a bitmap or a layer.
	gc           -- user initialized graphics context.
	x,y          -- center of ellipse.
	width,height -- size of ellipse.
	ang1,ang2    -- angle swept by wedge.

    RESULT

    BUGS

    SEE ALSO
	G_Arc()

giraffe.library/G_WhichLayer

    NAME
	G_WhichLayer -- tells which layer is foremost at coordinates.

    SYNOPSIS
	G_Layer G_WhichLayer( G_Layer a0:start, ULONG *a1:xy );

    FUNCTION
	  Checks to see which layer is exposed at the coordinates
	specified by xy.  The start layer can be anyone within the
	the layer tree.  This layer need not be mapped, so long
	as the pointer is valid by openlayer()/uselayer().  The
	coordinates xy are translated to the local origin of the
	returned layer.
	
	IMPORTANT!!!
	  This function calls G_DropLayer() on the layer that you
	pass and G_UseLayer() on the pointer that it returns for
	your convenience.  Please see the examples to see how
	this function is to be used.

    INPUTS
	start -- a valid layer pointer.
	xy    -- pointer to a coordinate pair in root coordinates.

    RESULT
	G_Layer  -- pointer to exposed layer.
	ALSO: xy -- coordinate pair is translated to local origin
	            of the layer.
    SEE ALSO
	G_UseLayer(), G_DropLayer()




